. Turning to two places rarely seen as a part of the Black experience, Japan and Okinawa, the book also presents the accounts of a group of Japanese scholars shaping the Black studies movement in post-surrender Japan and multiracial coalition-building in U.S.-occupied Okinawa during the height of the Vietnam War which brought together local activists, peace activists, and antiracist and antiwar GIs. Together these cases of Afro-Asian solidarity make known political discourses and projects that reworked the concept of race to become a wellspring of aspiration for a new society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxForeign public opinion, Japanese. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identityxHistoryx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with JapanesexHistoryx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with JapanesexHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teachingxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teachingzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnti-racismxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aAnti-racismxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aAnti-racismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnti-racismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814762653.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK